JOHANNESBURG &#8211; ANC veteran Kgalema Motlanthe has called on the party&#8217;s leaders leaders to step down at its consultative conference in June.The former deputy president of South Africa says the ANC top brass needs to acknowledge that the party is in crisis.During an interview with JJ Tabane on Power FM on Monday night, Motlanthe said the party s problems had filtered down to its branches.He blamed the current leadership for not leading by example.There has been specualtion in the media recently that Motlanthe might be a candidate to succeed President Jacob Zuma, but he scotched this possibility, saying it was a bad idea to recycle leaders.He did, however, say that the country was ready for a female president and that there were many women of integrity who could lead South Africa.